[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The **12 Mile Road–Kalamazoo River Bridge**, also known as **State Reward Bridge No.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] 53**, is a filled-spandrel concrete arch bridge in Ceresco, Michigan, that carries 12 Mile Road over the Kalamazoo River.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Built in 1920, it is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Plans for the bridge were developed by the Michigan State Highway Department from standard plans.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The structure was built by Calhoun County in 1920 as State Reward Bridge No.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Nichols, of Hastings, Michigan, for their bid of $25,175 submitted on March 11, 1920.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Construction cost $35,070, half of which was paid by the state of Michigan.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The bridge was listed on the National Register of Historic Places on December 22, 1999.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] It was eligible for its historical integrity and as a good example of the filled-spandrel design.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The 23 Mile Road–Kalamazoo River Bridge, also in Calhoun County, was added the same day.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] In July 2010, the Kalamazoo River oil spill affected the stretch of river that the bridge crosses.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The bridge is in the unincorporated village of Ceresco.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] A dam was previously located just upstream of the bridge, but was demolished in 2014 as part of the cleanup after the Enbridge oil spill.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The two-span bridge is 115 feet (35 m) long and has a filled-spandrel concrete arch design.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The arches are elliptical barrel vaults trimmed by a projecting string course.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The bridge's parapet railings, built of solid concrete, each have ten recesses.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] At the corners and middle of the railings are concrete lampposts lacking fixtures.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/12-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] At the northwest and southeast corners are affixed bridge plates.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The **1888 Minneapolis General Conference Session** was a meeting of the General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists held in Minneapolis, Minnesota, in October 1888.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] It is regarded as a landmark event in the history of the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner, who presented a message on Justification by Faith (Gal.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] White, but resisted by leaders such as G.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The session discussed crucial theological issues such as the meaning of "righteousness by faith", the nature of the Godhead, the relationship between law and grace, and Justification and its relationship to Sanctification.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The Seventh-day Adventist Church General Conference Session of 1888 was held in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] It was one of the most significant meetings the denomination had ever had up to that time since it was formally organized on May 23, 1863.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Church historians, theologians, and laypersons consider the session to be important.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] They differ in their own perspective and interpretation of the specific events, the message presented there, and the ensuing reactions.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The "joint Minneapolis Institute and General Conference, of 1888, involved vastly more than appeared on the surface.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The founding pioneers of the Seventh-day Adventist Church believed in Jesus Christ as their Lord and Saviour and the Bible as their guide in life.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Those who had come through the Millerite Movement had first-hand knowledge of disappointment and discouragement.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] As they studied the Scriptures concerning end time prophecy, the sanctuary types and their fulfillment, and the perpetuity of the law of God, they saw the necessity for organization as a means for proclaiming these truths to the world.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The denomination was formally organized on May 23, 1863, in Battle Creek, Michigan.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The men and women who were a part of the development of this denomination came from various religious backgrounds, bringing with them into the new movement some beliefs peculiar to their former associations.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Two significant hold-over theological views were semi-Pelagianism and semi-Arianism.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The focus of the early Seventh-day Adventist Church tended more toward basic denominational organization and development, emphasis on obedience to the Ten Commandments, and efforts at evangelism and church growth during the anguish of the American Civil War and its aftermath.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] After its formation the doctrines of salvation and righteousness by faith were understood and accepted but stayed in the background, mostly because these truths were familiar to most churches, so bringing out of these and other specific theological points awaited later focus and discussion.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Though their Biblical arguments brought many to the church, they had minimized the centrality of the indwelling Christ as the only power to obey the commandments and to keep the Sabbath, and self-satisfaction and complacency began to affect the church.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] By the second generation of the movement, the denomination had spread across the United States and had mission fields around the world.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] As the church grew, so did opposition (and in some places, persecution), particularly regarding the seventh-day Sabbath.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Emphasis on the Ten Commandments as a part of obedience to God was a firmly established and central tenet of the denomination by the 1870s.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Sunday-keeping Christians claimed that keeping the seventh-day Sabbath was a sign of legalism or judaizing.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Convinced of the Biblical correctness of the seventh-day Sabbath, Seventh-day Adventists turned to their Bibles to show the beliefs and doctrines from scripture and teach other Christians, prompting the moniker "People of the Book" to be applied to them, and not a few became decidedly legalistic.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] So at the 1888 General Conference Session in Minneapolis, the presentation of the message of Christ as the only source of righteousness by two young preachers was going to create conflict with some members including church leaders.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Ministers and laypersons alike used scriptures in debating the beliefs of Adventist, including this particular issue, from Scripture.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The Christ-centered gospel was displaced by man's efforts.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] A second issue that paved the way for the discussions at Minneapolis was the non-trinitarian view on the divinity of Christ.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] This was not an openly discussed theological perspective but was a view that many of the early church leaders had brought in from the churches they came from.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Some prominent writers and speakers, such as Uriah Smith, long-time editor of the Church's chief publication, held on to them firmly eschewing the idea of a creed, the denomination made no attempt at developing a systematic declaration of fundamental beliefs, or "Fundamental Principles," until 1872.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] A declaration of the nature of the Godhead and Christ as the fully divine "Son of God" appeared at that time.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] After the 1888 Minneapolis General Conference, additions on these subjects were made to the *Bible Readings for the Home Circle*, published by the Pacific Press.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Uriah Smith (1832–1903), long-time editor of the *Review and Herald* (now *Adventist Review*), the official organ of the Seventh-day Adventist Church, had expounded this position in his discourse on the Book of Revelation first published in 1865.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Another Adventist pioneer who held to what has been called by some in the denomination, the "Arian" or non-trinitarian view was Joseph H.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner was an early convert to the Advent movement, serving on the committee called in 1860 to form the legal organization of the denomination.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner succeeded James White as editor of the Pacific coast evangelistic magazine, *Signs of the Times*.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Through his several books on the atonement, the elder Waggoner wrote that Christ was only God in "a subordinate sense." His main point of dispute was the Trinitarian concept of three divine persons forming one Divine being composed of God the Father, God the Son, and God the Holy Spirit.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] In his expanded volume on the atonement, J.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner devoted two chapters in his attempt to prove that the Trinitarian view was false because it inferred that Christ, being God, could not have died on the cross of Calvary, and thus full atonement for sin could not have been made.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Other church leaders composing the majority of the founding Pioneers who espoused the belief in only one Divine being called "God," with Christ being the Divine "Son of God", were: James S.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] White (Ellen White's husband), Joseph Bates, J.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] A representative statement from these leaders is given here: "The Scriptures abundantly teach the pre-existence of Christ and his divinity, but they are entirely silent in regard to a Trinity." (J.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Church Founder and Prophet Ellen White wrote to clarify: "God is the Father of Christ; Christ is the Son of God.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] To Christ has been given an exalted position.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] All the counsels of God are opened to His Son." {8 Testimonies p.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] 268.3 1904} This language and other such widely accepted statements strongly upheld the non-trinitarian foundation of the early Seventh-day Adventist Church.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Still, more current SDA Church periodicals point out that the founding leaders of the Church are now regarded as in error on the topic of the Godhead since the SDA Church officially embraced the Trinity doctrine at the Dallas General Conference meeting held in 1980.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] One example of this is here: "Most of the founders of Seventh-day Adventism would not be able to join the church today if they had to subscribe to the denomination's Fundamental Beliefs...
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] More specifically, most would not be able to agree to belief number 2, which deals with the doctrine of the Trinity." (Ministry Magazine, Oct.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner was selected as a delegate from California to attend the 1886 General Conference session held that year at Battle Creek, Michigan.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] When he arrived he found that church leaders such as Butler strongly opposed his emphasis on Christ as the sole source of righteousness, especially in light of Waggoner's teaching on the law in Galatians.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Butler prepared a small booklet titled "The Law in the Book of Galatians" that was handed out to all the delegates at that conference, countering Waggoner's position.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Ellen White initially saw the conflict as a small diversionary topic but quickly realized the danger and that it was counter-productive to the real issue of the fulfillment of Adventist message of Christ's return and moved to resolve the uncomfortable situation.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Thus we find these two main points of contention facing the delegates at Minneapolis: justification is by faith not by works, and the view of the Godhead and its effect on the doctrine of the atonement.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Prior to the 1888 Minneapolis conference a third topic of contention developed between Uriah Smith and A.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Jones was an avid student of history, especially as it applied to the prophecies of the Bible.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] He had discovered that the Alemanni and not the Huns were one of the ten horns (tribes or nations) described prophetically in Daniel 7.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Smith took grave exception to this new view, relying on the traditional position of the Millerites to support his position.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Prior to the actual General Conference session, a Bible Institute was convened beginning on Wednesday Oct.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The General Conference session began on Oct.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] 18 and ran through more than two full weeks, ending on Sunday Nov.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] It was during the Bible Institute that A.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Jones delivered his evidence supporting the idea that the Alemanni were one of the ten horns of prophecy that succeeded the crumbling Roman Empire.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] No one was able effectively to dispute the historical evidence he cited in favor of the Alemanni's right to supplant the Huns as one of the kingdoms succeeding Rome.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Uriah Smith, Adventism's most noted prophetic expositor, was placed on the defensive.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] On one occasion he modestly disclaimed originality for the list of kingdoms he had given in *Thoughts on Daniel*.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] "Thus did a dispute over a minor point set the pot of controversy boiling before the really significant theological presentation began." "Many had come to the Conference expecting a clash, and so were not disappointed.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Such entered it in a fighting spirit, and a definite split developed.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] From the onset of the 1888 Minneapolis Conference, Ellen White perceived that a battle over truth was erupting within the denomination.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] At first, Ellen White rejoiced that the spirit of God was at the meeting and commented that the leaders "heard as it were God speaking to them through his Son.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Ellen White was convinced that God had "raised up" for this moment these two young ministers, E.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Jones, to give a message to the delegates at the conference."I believe without a doubt that God has given precious truth at the right time to Brother Jones and Brother Waggoner.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Do I say that they will not make a statement or have an idea that cannot be questioned or that cannot be error?
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Nor do I say that of any man in the world.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner arrived at the Conference, a blackboard had been placed on the speaker's platform with views on the law in Galatians written upon it.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner began to present what he had discovered from the Bible on the subject of Christ and His righteousness.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] "The preaching of the younger men (Waggoner was 33, Jones was 38) was trying to the older leaders.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Their vigorous preaching somehow seemed to have a note of authority that was resented." Supported in their resistance by letters of encouragement from G.I.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Butler to "stand by the old landmarks" these older men resisted what was being presented.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Morrison was selected to offer the rebuttal to Waggoner's presentations.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] He spoke sincerely and earnestly expressing the fear that Waggoner's view, if adopted, would direct attention away from the Adventist position of explicit obedience to all the commandments of God.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] When it was again Waggoner's turn at the pulpit, he and A.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Standing before the assembly they opened their Bibles and without personal comment alternately read sixteen passages bearing on the subject at hand.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Notwithstanding Ellen White's considerable influence to assist Waggoner and Jones, the debate over the law in Galatians soon became heated.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Placing righteousness by faith squarely on the foundation of Christ and His righteousness, and on Christ's work as our High Priest during the antitypical Day of Atonement, brought a fresh perspective to the doctrine compared to what was previously preached from Adventist pulpits.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Ellen White saw the importance of the 1888 message Jones and Waggoner brought and why it was needed for the members can be seen in her comments on the message of righteousness by faith.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] They needed to have their eyes directed to His divine person, His merits, and His changeless love for the human family.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] All power is given into His hands, that He may dispense rich gifts unto men, imparting the priceless gift of His own righteousness to the helpless human agent." Testimonies to Ministers, 92.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] "The uplifted Saviour is to appear in His efficacious work as the Lamb slain, sitting upon the throne, to dispense the priceless covenant blessings, the benefits He died to purchase for every soul who should believe on Him.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] John could not express that love in words; it was too deep, too broad; he calls upon the human family to behold it.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Christ is pleading for the church in the heavenly courts above, pleading for those for whom He paid the redemption price of His own lifeblood.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Centuries, ages, can never diminish the efficacy of this atoning sacrifice.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The message of the gospel of His grace was to be given to the church in clear and distinct lines, that the world should no longer say that Seventh-day Adventists talk the law, the law, but do not teach or believe Christ." Ibid.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] "If Christ is all and in all to every one of us, why are not His incarnation and His atoning sacrifice dwelt upon more in the churches?" Selected Messages, vol.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] "The faith of Jesus has been overlooked and treated in an indifferent, careless manner.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] It has not occupied the prominent position in which it was revealed to John.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Faith in Christ as the sinner's only hope has been largely left out, not only of the discourses given but of the religious experience of very many who claimed to believe the third angel's message." Ibid., 168.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] "A legal religion has been thought quite the correct religion for this time.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The rebuke of Christ to the Pharisees is applicable to those who have lost from the heart their first love.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] A cold, legal religion can never lead souls to Christ; for it is a loveless, Christless religion." Ibid., vol. l, 388.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Nonetheless, Waggoner's entire discussion on Christ and His righteousness was linked to the Sonship and thus the divinity of Christ.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] For Waggoner, the equality of Christ with God magnifies his condescension and humility in assuming humanity.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] 3:15) was that Emmanuel—God with us—would "save His people from their sin" (Matt.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Jesus fulfilled this promise in every aspect.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Such an expanded concept on the length and breadth of the atonement had never been heard before from any pulpit.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Ellen White declared it to be "a most precious message," a message that "was to bring more prominently before the world the uplifted Saviour, the sacrifice for the sins of the whole world.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Far from promoting antinomian sentiments, Waggoner's message presented Christ in all His glory as the Saviour of all mankind, it brought balance between Justification and Sanctification.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] When properly understood through a heart appreciation of what it cost the Godhead to redeem fallen man from sin, this truth results in a heart surrender to the will of God, producing faithful obedience to all the commandments of God.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] This was the message of Christ and His righteousness presented by E.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Jones at the 1888 Minneapolis General Conference.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Due to the conflict, Jones and Waggoner's presentations were coolly received or outrightly rejected by many of the leaders of the denomination, notwithstanding Ellen Whites words that it was the "old light", something that she had been preaching for decades.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Even so, these two men were invited to preach at subsequent camp meetings, worker's meetings, and ministerial institutes over the next several years.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner wrote extensively on the subject of Christ and His righteousness, developing the stenographic notes made by his wife during the 1888 conference into a book with that title.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Jones would be a principal speaker at the next several General Conference sessions, and would write an exposition on the work of Christ as our High Priest relating to the perfection of Christian character, titled *Consecrated Way to Christian Perfection* (1901).
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] 3:24], the Holy Spirit through the apostle is speaking especially of the moral law.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Although no manuscripts of the exact words from the 1888 conference are known to exist or preserved, save Ellen White's comments, in E.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Waggoner's book, Christ and His Righteousness, we are given a glimpse into what might have been said.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] These chapters (series of articles) are the first writings of Waggoner on the subject written in the early part of 1889 just weeks after the 1888 general conference session.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] The focus in this book, as well as other later books, like *The Gospel in Creation*, contain the building blocks with a definition of a true righteousness by faith theology and experience.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Namely the Holy Spirit's use of Power of the Word of God in the believer.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Meaning that because the Word has innate power by virtue of its supernatural origin and through the Holy Spirit's ability to use it, forms Christ within the believer.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Therefore, His righteousness internally replaces our internal unrighteousness.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] This concept has been lost sight of through the years in Adventist circles.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Other authors, such as Morris Venden, Hans LaRondelle, Desmond Ford and others, sort to emphasise it by promoting the classic Protestant positions on justification by faith.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Others have written their own books defining the tenets of what they believe Jones and Waggoner taught as the 1888 message.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] One tenet of belief heavily stressed by Robert Wieland and others was "Universal Justification".
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] This subject was not the foundation of Waggoner or Jones teaching.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Both men's books taught the concept of The Power of the Word as the central key, which is absent from all books written since the second half of the 20th century that attempt to define what the 1888 message is.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] It is unknown why Ellen White regarded E.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/1888-minneapolis-general-conference-adventist] Jones"s sermons, at the 1888 general conference, as the beginning of the Latter Rain.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The **23 Mile Road–Kalamazoo River Bridge** is a curved-chord through-girder bridge in Marengo Township, Michigan, United States, that carries 23 Mile Road over the Kalamazoo River.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Built in 1922, it is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Prior to construction of the concrete structure, the river was spanned by another bridge at this location, presumably of a steel truss design.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The new bridge was planned in January 1922 by the Michigan State Highway Department.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Calhoun County subsequently built the structure as a State Reward Bridge.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] Mead Brothers of Battle Creek served as contractor in dismantling the previous span and building the new bridge.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] It was eligible as one of the oldest examples of its design and for its well-preserved state.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The 12 Mile Road–Kalamazoo River Bridge, also in Calhoun County, was added the same day.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The bridge is oriented north–south and located about .25 miles (0.40 km) south of Marengo in a rural area.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The bridge has a curved-chord through-girder design, a style developed by the Michigan State Highway Department in the early 1920s.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The bridge consists of a single 60-foot-long (18 m) span.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The girders, which also serve as railings, have a curved top surface and, along the sides, have elliptical recesses with six smaller recesses within.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The corner posts have squared caps and bases to which are attached Armco guard rails.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/23-mile-road-kalamazoo-river-bridge] The northwest corner post bears a bridge plate.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] The **28 fundamental beliefs** are the core beliefs of Seventh-day Adventist theology.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Adventists are opposed to the formulation of creeds, so the 28 fundamental beliefs are considered *descriptors*, not *prescriptors*; that is, that they describe the official position of the church but are not criteria for membership.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] These beliefs were originally known as the **27 fundamental beliefs** when adopted by the church's General Conference in 1980.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] An additional belief (number 11) was added in 2005.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] The *Seventh-day Adventist Bible Commentary* is a significant expression of Adventist theological thought.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] They may be grouped into the doctrines of God, humanity, salvation, the church, Christian life, and the restoration.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Adventists have historically been reluctant to formalize a creed.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] In the October 8, 1861 Review and Herald, J.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Several summaries of Adventist theology have been presented at various times.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] They believe instead that God inspired the thoughts of the biblical authors, and that the authors then expressed these thoughts in their own words.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] This view is popularly known as "thought inspiration", and most Adventist members hold to that view.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] , urges Adventist Bible students to avoid relying on the use of the presuppositions and the resultant deductions associated with the historical-critical method.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] The Godhead (Trinity) consists of the Father, the Lord Jesus Christ, and the Holy Spirit.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] God, the Father, is a personal and spiritual Being, who is omnipotent, omnipresent, omniscient.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] He is of the same nature and essence as the Father.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] In addition, he took upon Himself human nature, living as a righteous man on earth, dying for the sins of mankind, raised from the dead and ascended to heaven where he makes intercession for mankind.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] The Seventh-day Adventist doctrine of creationism is based on believing that the opening chapters of Genesis should be interpreted as literal history.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Adventist belief holds that all Earthly life originated during a six-day period some 6000 years ago, and a global flood destroyed all land based animals and humans except for those saved on Noah's Ark.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Adventists oppose theories which propose interpreting the days of creation symbolically.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Although Adventists hold that creation week was a recent event, they believe the Bible speaks of other worlds populated by intelligent beings elsewhere in the universe, which pre-existed the Earth's creation week.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] first creation, the Earth was most likely His last one.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] of unfallen worlds meeting in God's presence somewhere in the universe.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Other inhabited planets are located in the vastness of space—well beyond the reach of space probes from our sin-polluted solar system, quarantined due to the infection of sin.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Adventists believe that inorganic matter was created prior to the creation week and was altered into its present form during the creation week.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/28-fundamental-beliefs] Therefore, the computed radiometric dates of standard geology are irrelevant to dating the creation of life on Earth.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Arnold Block** was a commercial building located at 12-14 East State Street in Battle Creek, Michigan.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1983.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Arnold arrived in Battle Creek in 1857 with his wife, Marla Dygert Arnold.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] He first ran a wooden pump-manufacturing business, gaining the nickname "Pump." After some time, he found that operating a hotel and saloon was more lucrative, and he ran the Arnold House (later renamed the Exchange Hotel).
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] The hotel and saloon quickly acquired an unsavory reputation, as Arnold repeatedly violated the city's liquor control laws and allegedly bilked travelers out of their change.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] However, business was good, and in 1886 Arnold constructed the Arnold Block.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] The block originally contained a restaurant and saloon operated by Arnold's son George H.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Arnold's office and storage for pawned goods.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Just as the Arnold House/Exchange Hotel had quickly acquired an unsavory reputation, the Arnold Block did likewise, with rumors of prostitutes and other shady characters.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Arnold was eventually convicted of the crime.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] He appealed, and while released, died himself in 1897.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] By this time, much of Arnold's assets had been lost to legal fees, and the Arnold Block was in the possession of the City Bank of Battle Creek.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] In 1896, the "Arnold Mission" for men hunting work was established in the Arnold Block, with the bank donating free rent.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Eventually the mission hosted a cheap lunch counter, free beds, and free baths.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] In subsequent years, the building housed a telephone company warehouse, a restaurant, a furniture store, billiard roan, barber shop, real estate office, cigar store, and office supply store warehouse.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] In the early 1980s, the building was refurbished to house an antique store, "Pump Arnold's Place." In 1988, the building was demolished to make way for the headquarters of the W.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Arnold Block was a four-story Late Victorian red brick commercial block with a flat roof.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] It measured thirty feet wide and fifty-one feet deep on one side, and sixty-five deep on the other.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] The building had a facade with extensive ornamentation, including an iron cornice and iron storefront elements, stone window surrounds, and decorative tile.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] On the first floor, the storefront held a plate glass windows framed by galvanized iron architectural piers and lintels .
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] To one side was a recessed entrance to the staircase leading to the upper floors.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] The store entrance was through wooden double doors with transom lights above.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] The second and third floors contained rock-faced window facings, lintels, and sills, above which were bands of sawtooth brickwork extending across the facade.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] On the fourth floor, more galvanized Iron trim surrounded the windows, as well as "bat-wing" and keystone trim between the windows.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adam-c-arnold-block] Above were the cornice with supporting brackets and frieze, also of galvanized iron.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] The **Advent Historic District** is a residential historic district, roughly bounded by North Washington Avenue, Champion Street, Hubbard Street, and Greenwood Avenue, in Battle Creek, Michigan.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] The district encompasses the heart of the former village of Washington Heights, which was developed as a by-product of the growth of the Seventh-day Adventist Church in the area during the last half of the nineteenth and the early part of the twentieth.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] The area was annexed into Battle Creek in 1926.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1994.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] The first European settlement of this area was by Elias Manchester, who came to the area from New York state in 1836.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] He constructed a log cabin, and a few years later a brick house, located at what is now the corner of North Washington Avenue and Manchester Street.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] He platted a portion of his property into 66 lots known as "Manchester's Addition." In 1852, lawyer and future Michigan Supreme Court Justice Benjamin F.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] Graves purchased the remainder of Manchester's farm.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] Around the same time, James Springer White and his wife Ellen G.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] White relocated the headquarters of the Seventh-day Adventist Church to Battle Creek.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] A number of Seventh Day Adventist figures, including the Whites, made their homes in the district.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] In 1889 Graves platted a portion of it into 124 lots, known as "Graves's Addition," and another section into 94 additional lots.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] The Manchester and Graves Additions together make up the Advent Historic District.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] Through the nineteenth century, the number of Adventists in the area grew, and by 1900 over 2000 Adventists lived in the neighborhood in and around the district.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] However, the church soon began decentralizing its activities, moving them to other communities, and as the twentieth century progressed, the number of Adventists living in the neighborhood gradually decreased.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] The Advent Town Historic District consists of an irregularly shaped area spanning several blocks of what was formerly the village of Washington Heights.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] It includes 181 residences, 173 of which contribute to the historic character of the neighborhood.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] Most of the homes were built in the latter part of the 19th century and early part of the 20th.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] The houses in the district include Colonial Revival and American Foursquare residences of brick and stucco, clapboard-covered Bungalows, and stylish American Craftsman houses.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/advent-historic-district] They were primarily built as single family homes, although some have subsequently been converted into multi-family rental properties.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Seventh-day Adventists and some smaller Adventist groups observe the seventh day Sabbath.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists has compiled that church's core beliefs in the 28 Fundamental Beliefs (1980 and 2005).
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] In 2010, Adventism claimed to have some 22 million believers who were scattered in various independent churches.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The largest church within the movement—the Seventh-day Adventist Church—had more than 23 million members in 2025.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Adventism began as an inter-denominational movement.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Its most vocal leader was William Miller.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Between 50,000 and 100,000 people in the United States supported Miller's predictions of Christ's return.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] After the "Great Disappointment" of October 22, 1844, many people in the movement gave up on Adventism.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Of those remaining Adventist, the majority gave up believing in any prophetic (biblical) significance for the October 22 date, yet they remained expectant of the near Advent (second coming of Jesus).
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Of those who retained the October 22 date, many maintained that Jesus had come not literally but "spiritually", and consequently were known as "spiritualizers".
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] A small minority held that something concrete had indeed happened on October 22, but that this event had been misinterpreted.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] This belief later emerged and crystallized with the Seventh-day Adventist Church, the largest remaining body.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Albany Conference in 1845, attended by 61 delegates, was called to attempt to determine the future course and meaning of the Millerite movement.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Following this meeting, the "Millerites" then became known as "Adventists" or "Second Adventists".
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] However, the delegates disagreed on several theological points.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Four groups emerged from the conference: The Evangelical Adventists, The Life and Advent Union, the Advent Christian Church, and the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The largest group was organized as the American Millennial Association, a portion of which was later known as the Evangelical Adventist Church.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Unique among the Adventists, they believed in an eternal hell and consciousness in death.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] They declined in numbers, and by 1916 their name did not appear in the United States Census of Religious Bodies.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It has diminished to almost non-existence today.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Their main publication was the *Advent Herald*, of which Sylvester Bliss was the editor until his death in 1863.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It was later called the *Messiah's Herald*.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Life and Advent Union was founded by George Storrs in 1863.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] He had established *The Bible Examiner* in 1842.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It merged with the Adventist Christian Church in 1964.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Advent Christian Church officially formed in 1861 and grew rapidly at first.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It declined a little during the 20th century.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Advent Christians publish the four magazines *The Advent Christian Witness*, *Advent Christian News*, *Advent Christian Missions* and *Maranatha*.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] They also operate a liberal arts college at Aurora, Illinois; and a one-year Bible College in Lenox, Massachusetts, called Berkshire Institute for Christian Studies.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Primitive Advent Christian Church later separated from a few congregations in West Virginia.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Seventh-day Adventist Church officially formed in 1863.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It believes in the sanctity of the seventh-day Sabbath as a holy day for worship.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It publishes the *Adventist Review*, which evolved from several early church publications.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Youth publications include *KidsView*, *Guide* and *Insight*.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It has grown to a large worldwide denomination and has a significant network of medical and educational institutions.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Miller did not join any of the movements, and he spent the last few years of his life working for unity, before dying in 1849.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Christadelphians were founded in 1844 by John Thomas.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] In 2000, there were an estimated 25,000 members in 170 ecclesias, or churches, in the United States.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Advent Christian Church** was founded in 1860 and had 25,277 members in 302 churches in 2002 in America.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It is a "first-day" body of Adventist Christians founded on the teachings of William Miller.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It adopted the "conditional immortality" doctrine of Charles F.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Hudson and George Storrs, who formed the "Advent Christian Association" in Salem, Massachusetts, in 1860.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Primitive Advent Christian Church** is a small group which separated from the Advent Christian Church.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It differs from the parent body mainly on two points.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Its members observe foot washing as a rite of the church, and they teach that reclaimed backsliders should be baptized (even though they had formerly been baptized).
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] This is sometimes referred to as rebaptism.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Seventh-day Adventist Church**, founded in 1863, had over 23,000,000 baptized members (not counting children of members) worldwide in 2025.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It is best known for its teaching that Saturday, the seventh day of the week, is the Sabbath and is the appropriate day for worship.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] However, the second coming of Jesus Christ, along with Judgment Day based on the three angels' message in Revelation 14:6–13, remain core beliefs of Seventh-day Adventists.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Seventh Day Adventist Reform Movement** is a small offshoot with an unknown number of members from the Seventh-day Adventist Church caused by disagreement over military service on the Sabbath day during World War I.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Davidians** (originally named **Shepherd's Rod**) is a small offshoot with an unknown number of members made up primarily of voluntarily disfellowshipped members of the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] They were originally known as the Shepherd's Rod and are still sometimes referred to as such.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The group derives its name from two books on Bible doctrine written by its founder, Victor Houteff, in 1929.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Branch Davidians were a split ("branch") from the Davidians.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] A group that gathered around David Koresh (the so-called *Koreshians*) abandoned Davidian teachings and turned into a religious cult.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Many of them were killed during the infamous Waco Siege of April 1993.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Church of God (Seventh-Day)** was founded in 1863 and it had an estimated 11,000 members in 185 churches in 1999 in America.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Its founding members separated in 1858 from those Adventists associated with Ellen G.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] White who later organized themselves as Seventh-day Adventists in 1863.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Church of God (Seventh Day) split in 1933, creating two bodies: one headquartered in Salem, West Virginia, and known as the Church of God (7th day) – Salem Conference and the other one headquartered in Denver, Colorado and known as the General Conference of the Church of God (Seventh-Day).
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The Worldwide Church of God splintered from this.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Many denominations known as "Church of God" have Adventist origins.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Church of God General Conference** was founded in 1921 and had 7,634 members in 162 churches in 2004 in America.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] It is a nontrinitarian first-day Adventist Christian body which is also known as the *Church of God of the Abrahamic Faith* and the *Church of God General Conference (Morrow, GA)*.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **Creation Seventh-Day Adventist Church** is a small group that broke off from the Seventh-Day Adventists in 1988, and organized itself as a church in 1991.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The **United Seventh-Day Brethren** is a small Sabbatarian Adventist body.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] In 1947, several individuals and two independent congregations within the Church of God Adventist movement formed the *United Seventh-Day Brethren*, seeking to increase fellowship and to combine their efforts in evangelism, publications, and other .
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Early in its development, the Bible Student movement founded by Charles Taze Russell had close connections with the Millerite movement and stalwarts of the Adventist faith, including George Storrs and Joseph Seiss.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] The various independent Bible Student groups currently have a cumulative membership of about 20,000 worldwide.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] According to the Watch Tower Society, there were about 9 million Jehovah's Witnesses worldwide as of 2025.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/adventism] Adventist churches only support marriage between one man and one woman.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The **Battle Creek Sanitarium** was a world-renowned health resort in Battle Creek, Michigan, United States.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] It was founded in 1866 on health principles advocated by the Seventh-day Adventist Church, and from 1876 to 1943 was managed by Dr.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The "San," as it was called, flourished under Dr.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Kellogg's direction and became one of the "premier wellness destinations" in the United States.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] After a devastating fire in 1902 the Sanitarium was not only rebuilt, but also enlarged.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] At its zenith, the sprawling health and wellness complex of more than 30 buildings situated on 30 acres accommodated near thirteen hundred guests.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] It housed a hospital with research facilities and a nursing school, as well as the Sanitarium Food Company, among others.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Kellogg in 1907, the physician stated that he and his employees were "independents" who "did not belong to any church" and that the Sanitarium promoted his theory of "biologic living" based on Adventist principles.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In 1928, a distinct 14-story addition to the main building, the "Towers," was constructed.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The Great Depression forced the institution to constrict and sell assets to serve its debt.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In 1942, the signature main building was purchased by the U.S.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Army and converted into the Percy Jones Army Hospital, and the sanatorium moved to the former Phelps Sanitarium building.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In 1957, the floundering wellness institution was taken over by the Seventh-day Adventist Church, which operated it under a different name until 1993, when it was sold.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The hospital was disbanded in the 1950s and the facility was managed by the General Services Administration.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In 2003, it was re-dedicated as the Hart–Dole–Inouye Federal Center.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] White presented the idea to create a health institution based on the newly developing health philosophy of the Seventh Day Adventist Church at the fourth session of the Church's General Conference in Battle Creek.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The leaders of the church, including Ellen's husband James S.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] White agreed, and construction began on the **Western Health Reform Institute**, which would later become the Battle Creek Sanitarium.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] On September 5, 1866, the Institute opened and began accepting patients, at first under Dr.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] John Harvey Kellogg became the medical superintendent, and his brother, W.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Kellogg put it, they took the word "sanatorium," which was defined back then as a health resort for invalid soldiers.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In his words, "A change of two letters transformed 'sanatorium' to 'sanitarium,' and a new word was added to the English language." Kellogg stated the number of patients grew from 106 in 1866 to 7,006 patrons in 1906.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In 1878, a new wooden structure known as the "Old Main" was built on the site, going through major redevelopments in 1884 and 1891.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The Old Main burned down in 1902 and was rebuilt in stone, 5-story high and enlarged.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In 1928, Battle Creek Sanitarium expanded with a 14-story high-rise with 265 guest rooms, called the "Towers," facing Champion Street.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The institution went into receivership in 1933, and the Sanitarium started to vacate its main facility.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Army purchased the main building and established the Percy Jones General Hospital; the hospital closed permanently in 1953 and one year later became the Battle Creek Federal Center.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Owned by the Seventh-day Adventists, the Battle Creek Sanitarium continued to operate as a psychiatric facility through the 1970s but closed its doors by the end of the decade.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] In 1986, the radial wings of the main building (the solarium, gymnasium and swimming pool) were razed, and the Sanitarium entered into the final chapter of its history, which formally ended in 1993.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Medical records have since been microfiched and are now kept by the nearby Fieldstone Center.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Along with high numbers of patrons, there was a large number of staff at Battle Creek.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Kellogg stated that "at the Battle Creek Sanitarium, the number of persons employed is never less than eight hundred, and often rises in the busiest season to more than one thousand." They comprised "physicians, nurses, helpers etc." There were 30 physicians on staff.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The sanitarium became a destination for both prominent and middle-class American citizens.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Celebrated American figures who visited the sanitarium (including Mary Todd Lincoln and Sojourner Truth) would influence and encourage enthusiasm for health and wellness among the general population.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] At the sanitarium, Kellogg explored various treatments for his patients, including diet reform and frequent enemas.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] He encouraged a low-fat, low-protein vegetarian diet with an emphasis on whole grains, fiber-rich foods, and most importantly, nuts.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Kellogg also recommended a daily intake of fresh air, exercise, and the importance of hygiene.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Many of the theories of John Harvey Kellogg were later published in his book *The Road to Wellness*.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Two three-story buildings, for men and women respectively, were devoted to hydrotherapy.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] This department employed both solar and electric light, with the latter used chiefly during winter.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Phototherapy held a prominent place at Battle Creek, where the first electric light bath was constructed.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Physical exercise was an important part of the Battle Creek system, facilitating not just the improvement of muscle tone, but also of posture, respiration, and of circulation and the facilitation of anabolic and catabolic functions enabled by circulatory processes.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Exercise included such components as postural, calisthetics, gymnastics, swimming, and passive methods such as mechanotherapy, vibrotherapy, mechanical massage.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Kellogg stated that exposure to the sun and open air was fundamentally important for health, including stimulation of the skin.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Battle Creek had a large outdoor gymnasium.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Again, the use of temperature differentials facilitated by water was a component, with exercise followed by a plunge into a fresh water swimming pool "just cool enough to be refreshing and invigorating," according to Kellogg's description of his own facility.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Patients were encouraged to sleep in the open air, and a range of outdoor activities were facilitated, from wood-chopping to basketball and other games, walking, trotting, and swimming lessons.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Also available were skating, tobogganing, skiing, and other outdoor sports (p.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Battle Creek utilized information as known at that time to provide nutritional requirements for health and well-being relative to each person's requirements.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Food required careful prescriptive preparation, with care also taken to ensure appetiveness and palatability were recognized.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] After the Wall Street Crash of 1929, few previously well-to-do patients came to the sanitarium.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Finances became very difficult for the "San" and the complex was put under receivership in 1933.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The sanitarium stayed in business until after the beginning of World War II.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Army, needing a hospital, paid $2,341,000 and moved in, creating Percy Jones Army Hospital.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The complex was later converted into a federal center and is currently named the Hart–Dole–Inouye Federal Center.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The Battle Creek Sanitarium was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1976.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The original listing included only the main building, a long six-story building in the Italian Renaissance Revival style, situated parallel to North Washington Avenue.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The listing was expanded in 2012 to include the 1928 tower, other buildings built prior to 1953, and the site itself.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] Battle Creek Sanitarium is depicted in the American 1994 film *The Road to Wellville* by Alan Parker, with British actor Anthony Hopkins playing a highly fictionalized Dr.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] This movie ends with the fire of the sanitarium building complex.
[src:battle-creek-sanitarium/battle-creek-sanitarium] The movie is based on the book of the same name by T.C.
